@NODE "What" "Introduction"
@{START}
@{CHAP1 "Introduction"}

@{NCT} is a simple utility to control NEC SCSI-I CD-ROM's.

Some of the NEC CD-ROM's have a SCSI-I interface, as opposed to most other manufacturers, which have a SCSI-II interface. Therefore most (all?) CD-ROM utilities are written to use SCSI-II commands, and have no or strange effects on NEC's drives.

As I am an owner of a NEC CD-R 210 drive, I have searched long and hard for any program that can a couple of simple tasks, such as ejecting the drive, playing music tracks, and so on. The only program I have found so far is »JukeBox« by Franz-Josef Reichert. However, although it's a great program, it wasn't what I wanted; a simple utility to quickly do these simple tasks.

Therefore I decided to write such an utility, and here it is, @{NCT}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"
@{START}
@{CHAP1 "Requirements"}

Of course, you need a NEC SCSI-I CD-ROM drive, such as for example the CD-R 210 or NEC CD-R 73.

In fact, I haven't tested if this porgram works with any other NEC drive than thoose, but it should.

Also you need a scsi interface. A CD-ROM filesystem isn't necessary, but it makes it easier for the program to find the CD-ROM drive.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installing" "Installation"
@{START}
@{CHAP1 "Installing"}

Installing @{NCT} is a simple task, just copy the program into a directory somewhere in your path. C: for example.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Using NecCDTool"
@{START}
@{CHAP1 "Using @{NCT}"}

The program is CLI only, and has the following template:

	@{CODE}VOLUME,D=DEVICE/K,U=UNIT/K/N,E=EJECT/S,L=LOCK/S,UL=UNLOCK/S,PT=PLAYTRACK/K/N,S=STOP/S@{BODY}

@{SUB2 "·"}VOLUME
Here you can specify the volume name of your CD-ROM drive. For example »CD0:«, which is default, i.e., if your CD-ROM drive is called »CD0:«, you don't have to specify this.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}D=DEVICE
After this keyword you can specifie the exec device name. For example »DEVICE scsi.device«. Note: if you specify a VOLUME name, specifying a device and unit is not necessary. Also, if your volume name is »CD0:«, you don't have to specify a device.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}U=UNIT
After this keyword you can specifiy the exec device unit number. For example »UNIT 4«. Note: if you specify a VOLUME name, specifying a device and unit is not necessary.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}E=EJECT
Ejects the drive bay..@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}L=LOCK
Locks the drive bay, preventing the user from opening it by pushing the open/close button on the drive.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}UL=UNLOCK
Unlocks the drive bay, making it possible to operate the drive bay manually again.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}PT=PLAYTRACK
Plays the specified music track if possible.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}S=STOP
Will stop any music playback.@{END2}

@{SUB2 "·"}LIST
Lists the contents of an audio CD, i.e. number of tracks, and track lengths.@{END2}

@ENDNODE

